06146nam a22009255i 9780812203776DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112006pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013938842  a(OCoLC)1037981857  a(OCoLC)1041979964  a(OCoLC)1046615695  a(OCoLC)1047025787  a(OCoLC)1049625668  a(OCoLC)1054879032  a97808122037767 a10.9783/97808122037762doi  a(DE-B1597)449215  a(OCoLC)979753837  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a823/.50935521 aThompson, Helen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIngenuous Subjection :bCompliance and Power in the Eighteenth-Century Domestic Novel /cHelen Thompson. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b3 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Ingenuous Subjection and Feminine Political Difference -- tChapter 1. Boys, Girls, and Wives -- tChapter 2. Mushrooms, Subjects, and Women -- tChapter 3. “The Words Command and Obey” -- tPart II. Ingenuous Subjection and the Novel -- tChapter 4. Eliza Haywood’s Philosophical Career -- tChapter 5. Charlotte Lennox and the Agency of Romance -- tChapter 6. Frances Sheridan’s “disingenuous girl” -- tConclusion. “Marriage has bastilled me for life” -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHelen Thompson's Ingenuous Subjection offers a new feminist history of the eighteenth-century domestic novel. By reading social contract theory alongside representations of the domestic sphere by authors such as Mary Astell, Mary Davys, Samuel Richardson, Eliza Haywood, and Frances Sheridan, Thompson shows how these writers confront women's paradoxical status as both contractual agents and naturally subject wives. Over the long eighteenth century, Thompson argues, domestic novelists appropriated the standard of political modernity advanced by John Locke and others as a citizen's free or "ingenuous" assent to the law. The domestic novel figures feminine political difference not as women's deviation from an abstract universal but rather as their failure freely or ingenuously to submit to the power retained by Enlightenment husbands.Ingenuous Subjection claims domestic novelists as vital participants in Enlightenment political discourse. By tracing the political, philosophical, and generic significance of feminine compliance, this book revises our literary historical account of the rise of the novel. Rather than imagining a realm of harmonious sentiment, domestic fiction represents the persistent arbitrariness of eighteenth-century men's conjugal power. Ingenuous Subjection revises feminist theory and historiography, locating the genealogy of feminism in a contractual model of ingenuous assent which challenges the legitimacy of masculine conjugal government. The first study to treat feminine compliance as something other than a passive, politically neutral exercise, Ingenuous Subjection recovers in this practice the domestic novel's critical engagement with the limits of Enlightenment modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDomestic fiction, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictionx18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFeminism and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryx18th century. 0aFeminism and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aFemmes et littératurexGrande-BretagnexHistoirex18e siècle. 0aFéminisme et littératurexGrande-BretagnexHistoirex18e siècle. 0aRoman anglaisx18e sièclexHistoire et critique. 0aRoman familial anglaisxH